What are the characteristics of a hit song?¶

By Casey Puentes

The dataset used in this analysis is available online at https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sashankpillai/spotify-top-200-charts-20202021.

Introduction¶

With the rise of new social media apps like TikTok, music is now practically unavoidable. A staggering number of 60,000 new songs (https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/over-60000-tracks-are-now-uploaded-to-spotify-daily-thats-nearly-one-per-second/) are uploaded to Spotify every day. While creators and the amount of music producdd is flourishing, not every song can be a hit with roughly 57,000 artists sharing 90% of the total streams on Spotify. Streaming services, like Spotify, give us helpful insights through data as to what characteristics some of the worlds most popular songs share.

For this project, I chose to use a dataset from Kaggle consisting of all songs on Spotifys top 200 chart from 2020 to 2021. This dataset includes many different types of information ranging from song name, to release date, and even to specific features of the song such as popularity and key. For my analysis, we will be using the following columns:

  • Song Name: The songs name
  • Streams: The total number of times a song has been streamed
  • Highest Charting Position: The highest position on the top 200 charts this song has ever reached between 2020 and 2021.
  • Number of Times Charted: The amount of weeks this song was placed on the top 200 charts between 2020 and 2021.
  • Artist: The Artist(s) for a given song
  • Artist Followers: The number of followers an artist has
  • Genre: The genre(s) of a song

The following are specific characteristics about a songs acoustics and flow. These will be very interesting to explore in terms of data analysis:

  • Popularity: Spotifys popularity rating of a song. Ranges from 0-100 with 100 being most popular.
  • Danceability: This value represents how 'danceable' a song is based on its tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. This value can be anywhere between 0.0 and 1.0 with 0.0 being least and 1.0 being most danceable.
  • Acousticness: A value between 0.0 and 1.0 that rates a songs acousticness.
  • Energy: The overall energy of a song typically measured by the tempo, loudness, and tempo of a song. This value is restricted between 0.0 and 1.0 with 1.0 being the most energetic.
  • Instrumentalness: The rating of a songs instrumentalness, or lack of vocals. Constrained between 0.0 and 1.0 where 1.0 is completely vocalless.
  • Liveness: An estimation of whether or not the given song was recorded with a live audience. Constrained between 0.0 and 1.0 where 1.0 is most likely to have a live audience.
  • Loudness: The average loudness of a song in decibles.
  • Speechiness: The more this song is filled with speech only (such as talk shows), the higher this value will be(0.0 to 1.0).
  • Tempo: The tempo or speed of the beat of a given song in BPM.
  • Valence: The positiveness conveyed by a song rated from 0.0 to 1.0 with 1.0 being the most positive.
  • Chord: The main chord of a songs instrumentals

Let's get started! :)

Now we have our dataset loaded into in a dataframe! Our next step is to tidy the data in whatever ways we can. Essentially, this just means that we need to make our data as complete and easy to use as possible so that during our analysis, we don't run into any issues or allow our data to be skewed. Typically, this consists of three main things: 1. Removing columns you aren't going to use, 2. Handling missing values, and 3. Converting data in the columns to the easiest-to-use/optimal forms(e.g. converting date strings to datetime objects). Let's start by removing the columns we don't need.

Now that our dates our stored accordingly, lets convert the genres object to something we can work with. Originally, I was thinking of converting the genres to a series or list and storing that in the column but after further consideration, that may not be the most efficient way to store this data, especially if we want to create a plot or graph based on genre popularity in the exploratory data analysis. Instead, we will use a very interesting method called "exploding."(https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.explode.html) This essentially turns each list element per song into its own row, making it easier to analyze. However, this can greatly increase the number of entries in dataframe, so we will store this exploded dataframe separately from the original.

In [14]:
# Create a deep copy of the data frame
dfExploded = df.copy(deep=True)

# Making the genres object easier to parse when exploding by removing the brackets and commas.
dfExploded["Genre"] = dfExploded["Genre"].apply(lambda x: x.replace('[', ""))
dfExploded["Genre"] = dfExploded["Genre"].apply(lambda x: x.replace(']', ""))
dfExploded["Genre"] = dfExploded["Genre"].apply(lambda x: x.replace("'", ""))

At this point, we have a copy of the dataframe with the genres column ready to be converted into an actual list and prepped for explosion. Lets now move forward with that list conversion and explode the dataframe based on the list genres.

In [15]:
# Create a list to store all of the genres in a row
genres = list()

# Get all of genres for a song, convert them to a list, and add them to the genres list for explosion.
for idx, curRow in dfExploded.iterrows():
    unparsedGenres = curRow["Genre"]
    
    # Split the genres by commas
    splitGenres = unparsedGenres.split(", ")
    
    if len(splitGenres) > 1:
        genres.append(splitGenres)
    else:
        genres.append(["no genre listed"])
    
dfExploded["List of Genres"] = genres

# Explode the genres dataframe
dfExploded = dfExploded.explode("List of Genres")

# Drop the old genres column as we don't need it anymore
dfExploded = dfExploded.drop(columns=["Genre"])

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Our data is tidy and ready to be analyzed further. There are many different avenues that we could move now in terms of analysis, but lets start simply by simply testing to see whether or not any of the features of a song have a linear relationship with Popularity. A great way to do this is scatter plots with Popularity and the other numeric features.

In [16]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plot

# Heres a list a of all of the different characteristics we are going to compare to popularity
columnsToPlot = ["Highest Charting Position", "Number of Times Charted", "Streams", "Artist Followers", "Danceability", 
                 "Energy", "Loudness", "Speechiness", "Acousticness", "Liveness", "Tempo", "Duration (s)", "Valence"]

popularity = df["Popularity"]

# Create a graph with popularity and each other column
for curCol in columnsToPlot:
    # Set up the plot
    fig, ax = plot.subplots(figsize = (10,10))
    plot.ylabel("Popularity")
    plot.xlabel(curCol)
    plot.title("Popularity vs " + curCol)
    
    # Plot the values and show the plot
    plot.scatter(x=df[curCol], y=popularity)
    
    # Plot a linear regression line
    slope, intercept = np.polyfit(df[curCol], popularity, 1)
    plot.plot(df[curCol], slope * np.array(df[curCol]) + intercept, color="red")
    plot.show()

The relationship that these characteristics share with the popularity of a song is not immediately visible. However, here are some of the things we can derive from these scatter plots:

  1. Many of the scatter plots have linear regression lines with seemingly no slope. This essentially translates to the fact that there is no correlation or relationship between these two characteristics.
  2. Some of the graphs do show a slight pattern, though, such as the danceability scatter plot in which songs that are more danceable than not are more likely to end up on the top 200 charts.

Each of these plots are densely packed with information. In order to make this analysis easier and condense the information, lets calculate the average of the data by grouping it by popularity. To achieve this, I will be using the groupby function.

In [17]:
# Create a graph with popularity and each other column
for curCol in columnsToPlot:
    # Set up the plot
    fig, ax = plot.subplots(figsize = (10,10))
    plot.ylabel("Popularity")
    plot.xlabel("Average " + curCol)
    plot.title("Popularity vs Average " + curCol)
    
    # Create a temporary dataframe to house the mean data
    dfTemp = df.loc[:, ["Popularity", curCol]]
    
    # Convert the popularity to integers and cur column information to floats for computation purposes.
    dfTemp["Popularity"] = dfTemp["Popularity"].astype(int)
    dfTemp[curCol] = dfTemp[curCol].astype(float)
    
    # Calculate the average value across all of the popularity values
    dfMean = dfTemp.groupby("Popularity").mean()
    
    # Plot the values and show the plot
    plot.scatter(x=dfMean[curCol], y=dfMean.index)
    
    # Plot a linear regression line
    slope, intercept = np.polyfit(df[curCol], popularity, 1)
    plot.plot(df[curCol], slope * np.array(df[curCol]) + intercept, color="red")
    plot.show()

With significantly less entries on the scatter plots, we are able to derive information much easier. For example, we can now see that the linear regression line for loudness is increasing from left to right, confirming that louder songs are typically more popular. These charts clearly show the relationship between a songs characteristics and their popularity, so lets move onto another interesting area: the chord of a song, to see if popular songs predominantly have any specific main chord.

In [43]:
import seaborn as sb

chordsFreq = dict()
numOfChords = 0

# Get the frequency of certain chords
for idx, row in df.iterrows():
    chord = row["Chord"]
    numOfChords += 1
    if chord in chordsFreq:
        chordsFreq[chord] = chordsFreq[chord] + 1
    else:
        chordsFreq[chord] = 1
        
xAxis = list()
yAxis = list()

# Consolidate the chordsFreq into the x and y axis lists.
for (key, val) in chordsFreq.items():
    xAxis.append(key)
    yAxis.append(val)
sb.set(rc = {'figure.figsize':(15,10)})
ax1 = sb.barplot(x=xAxis, y=yAxis, palette="Set2")
ax1.set_xticklabels(ax1.get_xticklabels(), fontsize=10, rotation=90)

# Add labels to the plot for easy reading
plot.xlabel("Chord", size=15)
plot.ylabel("Number of songs with Chord", size=15)
plot.title("Top 200 Songs by Chord", size=15)

Great! Now we have an easy-to-read bar graph consisting of the most popular main chords for hit songs. At a quick glance, we can see that the chords are all over the place in terms of frequency with D#/Eb being the least popular and C#/Db being the most popular. What this means is that songs that make the top 200 charts on Sptofiy mainly consist of the main chord of C#/Db while the least popular chord for charting songs is D#/Eb. Safe to say that if you want a hit song, make it in C#/Db!

With this information, we now understand a lot about what sort characteristics are more frequently associated with a hit song. Let's now try and see if we'll be able to leverage this information and make predictions about the next hit songs.

Machine Learning¶

Decision trees are a powerful tool for both classification and regression tasks in machine learning. They are easy to interpret and can be visualized, which makes them a popular choice. However, decision trees can be prone to overfitting, especially when working with high-dimensional data. In addition, decision trees do not perform well when the data is not linearly separable. When working with decision trees, it is important to be aware of these limitations. Let's move forward with our decision tree

I've decided to train the decision tree to determine whether a song is considered very popular (Popularity value >= 80) by using 5 different numeric features of the data:

  1. Energy
  2. Tempo
  3. Acousticness
  4. Liveness
  5. Duration (s)

We will first have to split our dataframe into two parts, one for training of the decision tree and another for evaluating its accuracy. Then, we'll have to use the training date to train the decision tree. Finally, we'll evaluate the accuracy overall.

In [42]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
import matplotlib.image as pltimg
from sklearn import tree

# Create new dataframe 
dfCopy = df.copy(deep=True)

# Create a new column based on whether or not the popularity of a song is over 80 (considered a very popular song)
popularityScore = []
for index,row in dfCopy.iterrows():
    if row['Popularity'] >= 80:
        popularityScore.append(1)
    else:
        popularityScore.append(0)

# Split the dataframe into two parts: One to train the decision tree and another to test the accuracy.
dfCopy['Popularity Decision'] = popularityScore
dfDecision = dfCopy[:800]
dfPredict = dfCopy[801:]

# The features our decision tree will be trained on
features = ['Energy', 'Tempo', 'Acousticness', 'Liveness', 'Duration (s)']

# Build the decision tree
X = dfDecision[features]
y = dfDecision['Popularity Decision']
dtree = DecisionTreeClassifier()
dtree = dtree.fit(X, y)
data = tree.export_graphviz(dtree, out_file=None, feature_names=features)

# Analyze the accuracy of the decision tree
predictions = dtree.predict(dfPredict[features])
trueValues = dfPredict['Popularity Decision']
accuracy = 0
for index, value in trueValues.iteritems():
    if value == predictions[i]:
        accuracy += 1
        
# Calculate the accuracy
print(str(accuracy/len(trueValues) * 100) + "% accuracy")

93.54838709677419% accuracy

Based on the decision tree input and the accuracy evaluation, we can confidently say we have an accurate way to predict whether or not a song will be considered very popular based on the given features. Woohoo! ML is cool!

We know that C#/Db is the most common chord for Top 200 songs and that songs that are more energetic and danceable are more likely to be on the top 200 charts.
